  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The research article titled \"Interphase chromosome conformation is specified by distinct folding programmes inherited through mitotic chromosomes or the cytoplasm,\" published in Nature Cell Biology, presents significant findings on chromosome folding programs. The study has garnered attention from various key institutions, including the University of Massachusetts Chan Medical School and the Howard Hughes Medical Institute, reflecting a robust institutional investment in this area of research.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The article, published in Nature Cell Biology in 2025, explores how interphase chromosome conformation is determined by specific folding programs that are inherited through both mitotic chromosomes and the cytoplasm. These findings are backed by a collaborative effort from distinguished institutions such as the University of Massachusetts Chan Medical School and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, illustrating a notable academic partnership in the field of cell biology.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The impact of the article is underscored by its citation in nine works, primarily from reputable venues including bioRxiv and Nature Communications. This trend indicates engagement from the scientific community and suggests that the research is influencing ongoing discussions and developments in the field of chromosome behavior and organization. The focus on such a cutting-edge topic demonstrates the article's relevance to both current and future research endeavors.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Moreover, the research received extensive funding from prestigious agencies such as the National Human Genome Research Institute (NHGRI) and the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID). This financial backing not only highlights the significance of the research but also reinforces the institutional validation of the work's impact on understanding chromosome dynamics and their biological implications.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The authors\u2019 commitment to disseminating their findings through open data is further exemplified by their use of platforms like GitHub and Zenodo for their datasets. This openness fosters transparency and collaboration within the scientific community, allowing for greater reproducibility and utilization of the data by other researchers. Such efforts contribute to a culture of shared knowledge and collective advancement in the field of genetics and molecular biology.</p>",
